properties.Summary:

Wind chill values near minus 55 are expected to return overnight into Saturday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Locations: Makkovik to Nain. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm in Nain, 20 to 25 cm in Natuashish, and 25 to 45 cm from Hopedale to Makkovik. Maximum wind gusts: north to northwest 80 km/h except near 100 km/h from Nain to Hopedale overnight tonight and Saturday morning. Time span: tonight and Saturday. Remarks: Snow will become heavy at times this evening and combine with strengthening northerly winds to create near zero visibility in blowing snow. Conditions are expected to improve Saturday evening. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected to develop. Under the snow squall, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow. Visibility in snow and blowing snow could significantly be reduced late this afternoon and evening as an Arctic front blasts through the region. The sudden onset of snow with strong winds will likely create visibilities near zero in blowing snow for a brief period of time as the front passes. Visibilities will improve late this evening in the wake of the front. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow will be mixed with rain today and snowfall of about 5 cm is expected. Heavy snow will begin late this afternoon or this evening when an Arctic front arrives. Along with the heavy snow, the Arctic front will bring northeast winds gusting to 60 km/h giving reduced visibility in blowing snow. About 15 cm of snow is expected tonight with an additional 5 to 15 on Saturday. Total snowfall accumulations are expected to reach between 30 and 40 cm by Saturday afternoon. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
